sql:
SELECT cancer_type_name, description, icd_code 
FROM cancer_types 
WHERE incidence_rate > 10 AND prevalence_rate > 10;

SELECT cancer_type_name, TRUNC(incidence_rate) AS Truncated_Incidence_Rate
FROM cancer_types
ORDER BY Truncated_Incidence_Rate DESC;

SELECT cancer_type_name, AVG(incidence_rate) AS average_incidence_rate
FROM cancer_types
GROUP BY cancer_type_name;

external_knowledge:
- Incidence rate > 5 and prevalence rate > 1 indicates cancers with higher occurrence and widespread cases;
- Even cancer type IDs: refers to cancer types with IDs divisible by 2;
- Accesses are only counted if the access ID is even, indicating some form of filtering or system-specific preference;
- The time span from the first to last access event highlights the period over which the data was accessed.

sql:
SELECT cancer_type_name, description
FROM cancer_types
WHERE incidence_rate > (SELECT AVG(incidence_rate) FROM cancer_types);

external_knowledge:
- 'Explorers' metaphorically refer to 'researchers'.;
- 'Mysterious lands of high-incidence cancers' refers to cancer types with incidence rates above the overall average.;
- 'Solar cycle of 2022' is a metaphor for the calendar year 2022.;
- 'Frequency of exploration' translates to the count of access events.;
- 'Average duration spent' refers to the average time spent accessing these cancer types in the registry.;

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT user_id) AS NumberOfUsers
FROM access_logs
WHERE data_accessed IS NOT NULL AND data_accessed <> '';

SELECT cancer_type_name, incidence_rate, prevalence_rate, survival_rate
FROM cancer_types
ORDER BY incidence_rate DESC;

